Consider an entangled system of two particles. It is observed that some measurement $A$ of the first particle yields a deterministic result. What can be deduced?
#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
Impossible for entangled systems
#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
Measurement on the second must be deterministic
#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
Spectrum of $A$ is degenerate
#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
There exists an operator on the second particle for which measurement is deterministic
